<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-912-296  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 912 296.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Micro  Oct 1989 v9 n5 p8(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Appropriate and inappropriate legal protection of user interfacesand screen displays: part 3, copyright law, the courts and theCopyright Office. (includes related article on series highlights)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Stern, Richard H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Protection of technological advances in intellectual property isan incentive to innovation.andP;  The Copyright Act passed by the USCongress in 1980 made it clear that computer programs were coveredby copyright laws; later court decisions found that object codeand ROM code were covered by the act as well.andP;  Patent laws alsoapply to computer programs, but the time and money involved havediscouraged their use to cover screen displays.andP;  Softwarecopyright holders may receive monetary damages against thoseinfringing on the copyright, and intentional infringement may besubject to criminal penalties.andP;  To prove infringement, the piratemust have had access to the work and must have created a versionsubstantially similar to the original.andP;  Copyright laws coverexpressions of ideas rather than the ideas themselves; legalquestions surrounding these issues are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CopyrightSoftware DesignLegal IssuesUser InterfaceScreensDisplaysPatent.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>